<TITLE> DU clashes halt admission form sales </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 18 (bdnews24.com) The sale of admission forms at Dhaka University was halted on Sunday after police clashed with students demanding changes in admission rules. The VC, proctor and other top-level university officials sat in an emergency meeting, DU security officer Quamrul Ahsan told bdnews24.com. A group of madrasa students began demonstrating on campus shortly before 9am protesting rules that barred them from seeking admission to new departments. As the students, under the banners of 'committee for protection of madrasa students rights' and 'Bangladesh madrasa students movement, tried to hold a rally in front of the TSC police barred them from gathering there. They again tried to rally and police charged them. Witnesses said some 10-12 students were injured. Large numbers of police were deployed at the TSC gate after the incident. A separate group of students, calling themselves 'progressive students' alliance, also began a demonstration from Modhur Canteen around 9:45 am pressing for cuts in admission fees. As they also approached the TSC, police again charged them leaving three students injured, said witnesses. After the incident the 'progressive students alliance' set up a blockade at the TSC. They also declared that they would not allow sale of any admission fees of B and D units until fees were lowered. A number of students who came to buy forms were also injured during the police chase, said people on the scene. Sales od A unit forms at Curzon Hall were also halted amid the demonstrations. bdnew
